                                              <h3 class="highlight header-colorize text-uppercase mb-4 mt-3"><a href="https://www.marshall.edu/academics/programs/physics-bs/">Physics, B.S.</a></h3>
                                              <p class="mb-4 size-18">Physics gives you a well-rounded education that develops your knowledge in the physical and natural sciences, including chemistry, astronomy, mathematics and engineering. As a Physics major, you’ll also explore the fundamental laws that govern the universe. Studying Physics also will prepare you for employment in non-physics fields with skills in programming and problem-solving, numerical literacy and creativity. Half of Physics graduates typically are hired directly after graduation and enter into the workforce; other Physics graduates choose to go on to graduate school.</p>
                                              <p class="mb-4 size-18">Physics is at the heart of nearly every activity we do in our daily lives. Earning your Bachelor of Science in Physics at Marshall University in Huntington, WV, will enable you to pursue challenging, exciting and productive careers in many specialized fields, ranging from nanotechnology, astronomy and astrophysics to medical physics, geophysics, physical chemistry, biophysics, engineering and more. Physics graduates also can go into such professions as law, dentistry and pharmacy.</p>
                                              <p class="mb-4 size-18">Physics also offers opportunities for many different career positions such as research and development scientist in government and national laboratories, industrial laboratory manager/technician, healthcare professional working in fields involving radiation, and becoming an educator/professor of Physics.</p>
                                              <h4 class="header-colorize">Why study Physics at Marshall University?</h4>
                                              <p class="mb-4 size-18">The Department of Physics offers a wide range of opportunities for both undergraduate and graduate students interested in pursuing research. Students can explore a diverse selection of research topics in nanoscience, nanotechnology, theory of condensed matters, nanoparticles, soft condensed matter research, water filtration, laser and phonon physics, optics and holography, remote sensing, gravitational waves, relativity and numerical physics, photovoltaic devices, thin film solar cells, optical astronomy, young sun-like stars and more.</p>
                                              <p class="mb-4 size-18"></p>
                                              <p class="mb-4 size-18"></p>
